pr_body:
A proposal on how to merge widgets together when they take multiple input types and how to separate out their handlers. This proposal uses a mixin and decorators to register different handler types to individual classes. While the implementation covers only `Orange.data.Table` type inputs, this will be expanded to all input types, so it will be able to be used in any widget that will need to handle multiple input types.
A toy example on how using the mixin should look:

```python
class Widget(MultiInputMixin):
    my_property = 1
    attribute = 'none'

    def set_data(self, data):
        pass

    def dummy_method(self):
        pass


@Widget.data_handler(target_type=InputTypes.DISCRETE)
class Discrete:
    attribute = 'discrete'

    def simple_method(self, *args):
        pass


@Widget.data_handler(target_type=InputTypes.CONTINUOUS)
class Continuous:
    attribute = 'continuous'

    def simple_method(self, *args):
        pass

```

A full example can be seen [here](https://github.com/pavlin-policar/orange3-prototypes/blob/cr-merge-widgets/orangecontrib/prototypes/widgets/owknn.py#L15-L76).

Also, since the widget gui needs to be updated in almost all cases when the widget receives new data, it might also be beneficial to add another decorator e.g. `@update_on_input` that would be added to methods that update the gui, and would automatically be called when the widget receives new data. This was, we would avoid the need to perform all updates in `set_data`, so it doesn't have to worry about the gui.

Pros:
 - All the methods and properties that handle a single input type are grouped together in the same class, which should make understanding and debugging fairly simple.
 - The very minimal API should make converting existing widgets that are separated to a single widget fairly simple.

Cons:
 - Pylint will undoubtedly complain in the handler classes since handlers will probably need to access properties of the base class, but since the handler methods are bound to the base class at runtime, they technically don't exist in the handler, hence the errors.

The implementation is not yet functional on orange widgets, there are still several issues I need to work out, but any comments or suggestions on the API would help a great deal.

Change urlpatterns to plain list of django.conf.urls.url() instances as patterns() has been deprecated since 1.8;

Replace django.core.context_processors with django.template.context_processors when importing csrf as django.core.context_processors is deprecated in favor of django.template.context_processors

Removes Django1.10 warnings in django 1.9

As for now I would like to exclude the new image functions from the API. So I added a warning to the DOC-string. The warning is also printed when one of those functions is used.
That way we are still a bit more flexible with what we are going to do with the image-print-functions.

@python-escpos/dev any objections?

Fixes #5685 and adds integration tests to prevent regressions.

The issue is now we sometimes use an `AuthHandler` instance multiple times when previously it was only used once. Continuously adding to the list of authorizations and trying to solve the challenges again makes boulder mad (it errors saying we're trying to modify a failed challenge), so let's limit the scope of `aauthzrs` to the `handle_authorizations` method.

@ohemorange, if you have time to quickly review this, it's valuable as you're the most familiar with the changes here, but if not @joohoi, it'd be great if you could take a look. All we should be changing is we now pass the variable around rather than keeping it on the class and adding tests so it should be pretty straightforward.

Adds Sohail's benchmark to the codebase. Replaces #959 

This PR omits the asv-related part of #959, since it was my (perhaps incorrect) impression that the asv integration never really got up and running. If it did, we can include it in a separate PR later.

@QCoDeS/core
